    <!-- Add at least 3 examples -->

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate <m>log 3 + log 5 - log 3</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
               <p> <term>Step 1:</term> Since <m>log a + log b = log (a \times b)</m>, 
                 we can write <m>log 3 + log 5</m> as <m>log (3 \times 5)</m>,
                 which simplifies to <m>log 15</m>. </p>
               <p> <term>Step 2:</term> Now, we can rewrite the expression as <m>log 15 - log 3</m>. 
                 Since <m>log a - log b = log (a \div b)</m>, this simplifies to
                 <m>log (15 \div 3)</m>, which is <m>log \\ 5</m>. 
             </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate <m>log 100 - log 10</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
              <p>
                    Since <m>log a - log b = log (a \div b)</m>, we can write
                    <m>log 100 - log 10</m> as <m>log (100 \div 10)</m>, which simplifies to
                    <m>log 10</m>. 
              </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Calculate <m>log_2(8)</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
               <p>
                 We can rewrite <m>log_2(8)</m> in exponential form as
                 <m>2^x = 8</m>, where <m>x</m> is the value we want to find.
                    Since <m>2^3 = 8</m>, we can conclude that <m>x = 3</m>, which means:
                 <m>log_2(8) = 3</m>
              </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

